p.s:
We can recall that the probability of a simple event can be written as
        \begin{align*} \text{@probabilityofanevent } = \frac{\text{@numberofoutcomeswheretheeventoccurs}}{\text{@totalnumberofpossibleoutcomes}}. \end{align*} 
		In this case, we need to calculate the probability of selecting a girl, which we can write as $@P \left( \text{@girl} \right)$.

We recall that divisible means to be able to divide by a number and get an integer answer. Numbers that are divisible by 5 are also multiples of 5. We can list the numbers that are divisible by 5, between 1 and 81, as 

	    \begin{align*}5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, 50, 55, 60, 65, 70, 75, \text{@and }80. \end{align*}

	     As the highest card value is 81, then there are no higher possible values. Counting these values, we see that there are 16.

Multiplying both sides of this equation by 28 and simplifying gives us
		\begin{align*}
		    28 \times \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) &= \text{@numberofmen}\\
		    14 &= \text{@numberofmen}.
		\end{align*}

Counting the number of even digits above, there are 6 even values. The total number of digits is 9. Substituting these values into the probability equation above gives us
		\begin{align*}
		    @P \left( \text{@evendigit} \right) &= \frac{6}{9}\\
		                                                            &= \frac{2}{3}.\end{align*}

We can check our answer by calculating that the number of red balls must be $31 - 24 = 7$. Thus, the probability of picking a red ball would be the given value of $\frac{7}{31}$, since
		\begin{align*}
		    @P \left( \text{@red} \right) &= \frac{\text{@numberofredballs}}{\text{@totalnumberofballs}}\\
		                 &= \frac{7}{31}.
		\end{align*}
